name: NPR
text:
Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine is expected to sign a bill requiring fetal remains from surgical abortions to be cremated or buried after the state Senate agrees with changes made by the House. 

An ACLU lobbyist calls it "nothing more than legislative harassment."
https://t.co/Jh6k8B8u7j

name: NPR
text:
JUST IN: A federal judge has ordered the Trump administration to fully restore DACA and begin accepting new applications as soon as Monday. An estimated 300,000 undocumented youth in the U.S. would be eligible for its protection.
https://t.co/uv50PvbvS2

text:
The Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine was developed fast. But a leading vaccine expert says "it's really important for people to understand that while the timelines have been compressed, they haven't cut corners with respect to proving safety or efficacy."

name: NPR
text:
China's lunar probe Chang'e-5 is headed back to Earth after collecting soil and rock samples. The spacecraft planted a flag, making China the 2nd nation to leave its national banner on the moon.
https://t.co/dh2GNdwJlF

name: NPR
text:
In July, Nick Baldetti resigned as director of Kansas' Reno County Health Department. The reason? A hostile political environment and threats to his family.

"I had the local police watching my house."
https://t.co/DV2OlWs5Oj

name: NPR
text:
The Ad Council will recruit trusted influencers for its $50 million campaign to convince people to take the COVID-19 vaccine. It's "our moonshot moment," the council's CEO said.
https://t.co/0zANorx85o
